The secret of splendor over Norway solved: the Russians tested a missile
Over Norway a special light effect of unknown origin was observed.
The Russian Defense Ministry ended up acknowledging yesterday that near the borders with Norway it tested an ICBM.
The launch failed again. The &quot;Bulava&quot; -type missile, previously intended to be the pride of the Russian army, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Even their repeated presence in missile tests has not had the desired effect on the success of test flights.
Bulavá, in most cases, did not fly off or there was a failure in the air.
In the Russian newspapers they write of &quot;Bulava&quot; as of &quot;a missile that does not fly&quot;.
A missile that does not fly, but shines.
During this, the 13th test, there were no problems at first.
At the end of the flight, technical problems occurred again in the aircraft.
The engine probably exploded in the third stage of the missile.
This time &quot;Bulava&quot; was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which floated submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile makes it possible to launch from a ship that is moving and is submerged at the same time.
That is why it is likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed &quot;Bulava&quot;.
The Norwegians did not hesitate from the first moment that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by affirming that one cannot simply speak of a failure.
The first two stages of the missile held and the failure occurred in the third.
In the previous cases the engines broke down immediately in the first stage.
Although none of the launches went completely without errors, according to the Ministry of Defense management only six of the thirteen were unsuccessful.
