A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the &#39;calloused&#39; HIV virus
The team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some drugs already available.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged thanks to a mixture of drugs that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If virus replication is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metallocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon, and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way than all drugs used today, and therefore can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work the scientists find new, &#39;improved&#39; compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the albumin of the virus.
Metallocarborans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are linked by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
The HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV protease, splitting of the HIV virus does not occur and mature, infectious virus corpuscles would not be created.
If we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient&#39;s body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In an article published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds, in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which continues to be systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective
The test of the effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease was carried out in a test tube, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from patients with HIV.
The effect of metallocarborans in the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect in resistant variants, in which the drugs often do not work.
The unique effect mechanism, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications makes, that metallocarborans are interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, the head of the Structural Biology laboratory at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
