The pneumococcal vaccine will be free and voluntary
The pneumococcal vaccine from January will put an end to the usual customs.
As the first vaccination it should be free for families and at the same time voluntary.
However, opinions already appear that the mandatory vaccine would be more effective.
Preparations for the introduction of the free pneumococcal vaccine are complete.
The Institute of Medicines is already setting the maximum prices for vaccines, which will be covered by insurance companies.
The experts also already have it clear in the vaccination procedure.
The new vaccine
Free vaccinations for children born in August
As of January, children born since August 2 of last year will be able to receive the pneumococcal vaccine free of charge.
The condition is not having received a dose of the vaccine before.
Those who started the vaccine last year or earlier have to cover other doses of the vaccine as well.
The first dose of the vaccine must be received between the third and fifth month of age of the child.
Last year, a quarter of families voluntarily allowed their children to be vaccinated against pneumococci.
The parents however paid for a dose 1600 crowns and more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate younger children.
Experts generally estimate that insurance companies will spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns annually on vaccines.
However, they will save on treatment, which is needed for unvaccinated children.
So far the state has spent approximately 500,000 annually on vaccinating children.
Covered vaccination was initiated by the so-called Janota package.
Pneumococcus is the cause of otitis media, but also of serious infections including meningitis and septicemia.
Of pneumococcal infections in our country every year, according to research in hospitals, 28 children no older than 10 years of age die.
In addition to the Czech Republic, pneumococcal vaccine coverage in children was introduced in approximately 40 countries.
Will the vaccine be mandatory?
However, opinions appear at the same time that this vaccine could be mandatory in the future.
As of January it must be covered by insurance companies and voluntary.
Compulsory vaccination would be better, said Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association, for example.
Your association has been propagating pneumococcal vaccines for a long time.
Experts at an international conference, in which our association participated, were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have the voluntary vaccine.
It is not completely ideal.
On the other hand, we are happy to achieve at least this.
I think this is the path we now have to take, Kalovský mentioned.
The Ministry of Health, however, does not want to change the pneumococcal vaccination procedure.
At this time we are not thinking about it at all, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccine has its downsides, doctors say
The president of the pediatric society Odborná společnost praktických dětských lékařů Hana Cabrnochová acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks.
If all children would receive the vaccine, one can reason about reducing the number of doses. &quot;In the situation, when the vaccine costs such a high amount, we relatively understand the political decision to have started the vaccination as voluntary,&quot; says Cabrnochová.
Experts hope that as of next year more than 80 percent of young parents will allow their babies to be vaccinated against pneumococci.
The pneumococcal vaccine is a big change also because as the first vaccination in children it is covered by health companies, not by the state.
Insurance companies should spend more money on prophylaxis, to save on treatment later, Cabrnochová explains.
Doctors will have to buy the vaccines themselves.
However pediatricians are concerned about purchasing vaccines.
Previously, vaccines had to be purchased by insurance companies and distributed to doctors, just like when the state gives them other vaccines.
Some deputies, however, were afraid that the insurance companies could &quot;take the money out of health insurance.&quot;
Doctors will therefore have to buy the vaccines and wait, until they are paid for by the insurance companies.
It is estimated that pediatricians will invest 40 thousand a month in vaccines, which is a remarkable sum.
It will not be easy at all, says Cabrnochová.
