The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by defiant stances and mutual recriminations, garnered renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that envisions ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrialized nations that bear most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and outlined the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
