This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what top UN climate official Yvo de Boer described as &quot;the big picture.&quot;
It shows the profiles for a possible deal, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25-45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would cut theirs during the same period between 15 and 30 percent.
Together, the countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred talks on Friday, promising to provide $ 3.6 billion annually for the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Still, the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated conversations last week was featured on Friday.
US special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory greenhouse gas emission cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the world. developed.
