Managerial Revolution or End of Business Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain ...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies with respect to consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to certain &quot;values&quot; from above, as before, it was a matter of imposing products designed by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to strategies to conquer markets ... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeat regularly.
An employee demobilization can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R&amp;D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) &quot;requires that all parties involved (...) have a proactive behavior and a forward-looking vision&quot;; it requires a commitment from employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian leadership.
For this reason, we call for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company&#39;s concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls are relatively useful
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I&#39;m afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, faced with a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially ... what they always did! B989
-Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanistically.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behaviorist theory that the American &quot;neurosciences&quot; recently reactivated, and widely disseminated behind their backs by the Institutes of Studies and the media.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the &quot;commands&quot; (sic) of executive commitment, a recent Ipsos research published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management stance, unadapted to today&#39;s world .
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies, supposes adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating in all reasoning or business management practice, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects come true.
Today, only studies from Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, company managers can monitor, anticipate and anticipate their &quot;social performance&quot; and relocate human resources management &quot;in place.&quot;
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
