The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa Hallae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with claws. sickle-shaped and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa Hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the journal Science Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
The researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected a total of the remains of five specimens.
A find confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name &quot;Tawa&quot; comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional find: &quot;Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found.&quot;
Other dinosaur experts don&#39;t quite share that enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it does confirm some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn, for example.
According to the current current of opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, about when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as &quot;neck long &quot;and its relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa Hallae is a primitive theropod.
It shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, the researchers found evidence of air pockets in the skull of Tawa Halbee, like those also found in the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to the air pockets, the respiration of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa Halæ also the bones of the spinal column were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbagged theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of later giant sauropods also possessed air pockets and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers deduce that saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single land mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa finds the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
All three cannot be descended from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We think there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the Science study.
Naturally, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group to the dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Your opinion could give a distorted picture, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line of reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic the dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while the kinship died out at the borderline from Triassic to Jurassic.
Success stories weren&#39;t forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories don&#39;t always last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
