In the waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of the mentally ill and drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality are blurred.
As long as it occurs during sleep, everything is in order.
When we are lying in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can indulge unimpededly into the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states while waking, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be a madman or a drug addict, or at least a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or the drugged.
It is our imagination to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes blur the lines between dreams, madness and reality.
The dreamlike states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, psychedelic experiences of New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, states of shamanic possession, and psychoses and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin, and acetylcholine - has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disturbed.
During a schizophrenic psychosis complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts appear very frequently.
Gravity no longer has power over him
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of dream in waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a &quot;great similarity of the state of madness with dream states&quot;, for Sigmund Freud, the dream even it was &quot;a psychosis, with all the nonsense, crazy formations, and mirages of it.&quot;
It is the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over him, he is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of winged demons, with blood-red grimaces, misshapen, gnashing their teeth.
They are chasing him, they kick him with heavy flaming boots, they throw him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Strident and evil voices echo from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. plucks two cables from the stereo, ties them together to form a hangman&#39;s knot, and fixes them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs on a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump
The rope is released.
Let this be a lesson to you! The voices shout in a chorus that bursts his eardrums, &quot;Go to the clinic and get cured!&quot;
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population falls ill with schizophrenia at least once in their life; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common illness after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or mania. persecutory.
Hearing voices is especially widespread: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like dreams, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
Perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed to him.
At the same time he enters a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
In general, it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in their life
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, &quot;the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remain in principle as is.&quot;
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are supported by reality, distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers it is still a mystery why our brain pranks.
According to Fuchs, states of exception can lead anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral illness of the mother during pregnancy, explains Fuchs.
But it remains unknown how this alteration of the neural system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Also the influence of the environment plays an important role - stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when there is already a previous disposition.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis by interfering with the brain&#39;s transmitter system.
When the brain gets hot
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experiment with some, says Lübeck professor of psychology Erich Kasten.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on your point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our heads), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, along with mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer&#39;s and head injuries.
surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer from hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or little self-conscious; when our brain gets hot, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, lovesickness or other exceptional brain states.
In jüngeren Studien gab bis zu einem Drittel der Befragten an, mindestens einmal im Leben eine Halluzination erlebt zu haben.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it weren&#39;t for those images and the voices.
Sometimes during recess, a clumsy boy with long dark hair happens to speak to him.
When she answers him, the other students look at her in surprise; nobody, apart from her, hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a bit of a strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she is not dreaming.
She is awake and sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next to her.
You can even feel their presence, for at least a few moments.
It&#39;s a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Sometimes she wonders if she is crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class sometimes he cannot follow the lesson because the teacher - to his eyes and ears - is introducing a new classmate, while for the rest he is visibly and audibly explaining the mathematical equations.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While she waits in the dark room for sleep, which is often late and rare, she cannot tell if she is awake or dreaming, if the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, appear in front of your open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
She has not told her parents and friends anything, they would think she is crazy.
Fall 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have disappeared for a year.
Since she has come into contact through the Internet with the psychologist Kasten, she knows that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while they will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is idle and is in charge of finding entertainment itself.
Sarah K., an only child, was scared of other children as a child and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he has called dad since he can remember is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, sufferers like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. “Every experience,” says Kasten, “takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real. &quot;
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, psychically healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients appreciate their hallucinations as a special ability.
Borderline situation between dream and hallucination
In this overly conscious world, imaginary experiences often become pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor at Heidelberg and chief physician at the psychiatry and psychotherapy clinic at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful illness, but it also involves something positive and creative - insanity is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that later cannot differentiate from being awake.
Dreamlike conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or illness, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische Lähmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with an own and imaginary world that is uncoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between dream and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation is still present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, from Zurich, describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-saving action.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on trips of several days after a heart valve operation including a heart transplant, while his body was condemned to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by himself and visited strange places of other times: he was bedridden, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watched over his health.
He saw himself in the early Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the snowy Alps and came across a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary events, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, this is how you describe your experience.
On the contrary, the memories of the mental trips are, many years later, much clearer, even in the irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the internal reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes the psychologist Kasten, &quot;can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.&quot;
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
