75% of working mothers have had labor problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study &#39;Fertility and labor trajectory of women in Spain&#39;, prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey carried out among 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt in this regard: 75% of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of coexistence as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start living together as a couple earlier, carry out their first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
&quot;Women between 35 and 49 years old with a permanent job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting coexistence, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with permanent jobs have needed more time of their life trajectory to get them, which has led them to postpone the union and the arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a great influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of the match, &quot;explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they get married and when they have the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and have their first child.
The difference is also maintained between women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years old, those with elementary and higher education became mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
&quot;There is also another division between women based on their level of studies.
While those with elementary studies marry and have their first child before finding a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a new one. son &quot;, details Delgado.
