Manuel Vicent gives away in &#39;Póquer de aces&#39; (Alfaguara, illustrations by Fernando Vicente) some thirty X-rays of writers who have passed through his literary life (and, in cases, also through the other).
He does not do it in the foreseeable and fearsome genres (biographical sketch, life and work), but rather looking for something similar to the nucleus of ignition of the creative character.
The trip has its excitements and Vicent does not spare scares or illuminations.
Besides an exquisite pleasure, the book is a moving invitation to readings and re-readings.
Here are some snapshots.
On Albert Camus: &quot;In its pages I discovered that the Mediterranean was not a sea, but a spiritual, almost physical drive, the same that I felt without giving it a name: pleasure against unfortunate fate, morality without guilt and innocence without any God.&quot;
On Samuel Beckett: &quot;Nihilist, allegorical Christian, wrote what he had in his blood, not in his intellect, between impotence and ignorance, with a dazzling poetic humor, meaningless, like the blade of the knife that was about to kill him . &quot;
On Graham Greene: &quot;Our man was abducted by this woman with a passion that lasted thirteen years, in whose flesh he combined the emotion of adultery with the pleasure of remorse, a spiritual privilege that consisted of reaching heaven through the path of perdition. &quot;
About James Joyce: &quot;The &#39;Ulysses&#39; was published in Paris in 1922 by Sylvia Beach. It is one of the eight thousand meter peaks of world literature, which must be climbed by the north wall, from which a and again the best mountaineers. &quot;
On William Faulkner: &quot;He was a weird guy.
Of himself, he sometimes said that he was the heir of a county landowner and other times that he was the son of a black woman and a crocodile.
Both dreams were of grandeur. &quot;
On Louis-Ferdinand Céline: &quot;This writer picked up the insane cry thrown from a bridge by that Munich character to carry its echo deep into the night of the 20th century in its literary form and he did it on a journey fleeing from himself and invoking posterity with a violent speech to worms. &quot;
On Dorothy Parker: &quot;One day she got down on her knees and prayed, &#39;Dear God, I beg you to make me stop writing like a woman.&#39;
On Joseph Conrad: &quot;On his grave these verses by Spenser were engraved: &#39;The dream after the effort, / after the storm the port, / the rest after the war, / after life is very pleased with death.&quot;
On Virginia Wolf: &quot;In her luggage she also brought her depressions.
Her husband accepted with all normality that she told him that Edward VII was spying on her among the azaleas or that the birds were singing in Greek.
There has never been the case of a man so patient and in love with a neurotic whose literary talent was ahead of his madness. &quot;
On Pío Baroja: &quot;What did Martín-Santos do but try to inoculate Joyce in Baroja?
What did Benet try but to pass Baroja through Faulkner&#39;s weapons?
What did Cela do but abduct the man&#39;s fame so that he could serve as her own pedestal? &quot;
Cowardly aggression
Last week, my 70-year-old mother was walking through our neighborhood in the municipality of Fuenlabrada when a group of young people between 15 and 18 years old passed her and our dog, a mestizo breed, rescued from the kennel. and with no more than six kilos of weight and, without a word, they gave him two kicks that left the dog badly injured.
Our outrage is capitalized because we do not find fun in a gratuitous attack on a small and defenseless animal, which by the way, was tied up.
To this must be added the suffocation that caused a lady who was walking quietly and who, when she rebuked these individuals, came to fear for their physical integrity, since a madman who attacks an animal is capable of doing the same with a woman, a child, an old man or, in short, with anyone who is weaker than himself.
