Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As it happened with the ABS anti-lock brakes and will happen with the ESP stability control, the emergency braking aid systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they already are in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while a grace period is set for the rest until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians although, due to the way they work, it can also help avoid many rear-end collisions.
What the emergency braking assistant does is increase the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency, which the system detects by the stomp of the driver.
But this one does not always maintain that pressure until the end.
According to a study carried out by the manufacturer of automotive components Bosch, a third of the drivers involved in an accident had not hit the brakes before the collision and half of them did not use their full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the other hand, aid intervention demands the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance the car takes to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or a camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to slightly acting on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, help him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
In the event that it does not react, and even if the collision is unavoidable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
