After the days of wine and roses since last spring in which asset inflation has been the dominant trend in the markets, once again uncertainty reappears in the markets, which should not be surprising since it is its natural state, in an environment in which agents make decisions about the future by nature uncertain.
The medicine used by central banks to stabilize the markets was to monetize debt with the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving a free bar of liquidity at rates close to zero so that financial institutions could buy assets to discount.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have practically ended and, without questioning their heterodox liquidity policy, they are beginning to throw some sand in the gears as the ECB did with its next week&#39;s year-end auction.
Investors therefore doubt the ability of the world economy to sustain economic recovery without such heterodox measures and we are witnessing a reversal in the reduction of risk premiums.
Stock market volatilities and corporate bond spreads have picked up again, although they are still far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
The states were forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
Again there is a flight to quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the haven chosen by investors, causing a widening of the spreads of the eurozone countries with respect to Germany.
Spain had hardly been affected by this episode of instability but Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s arrived and threatened a further downgrade of the Kingdom of Spain&#39;s rating.
On the other hand, some uncertainty does not hurt to silence the defenders of moral hazard who were once again trying to create a conscience on those responsible for world economic policy for having stopped the destructive effects derived from the credit restriction on the destruction of employment, when what should be done is to decree a new Thanksgiving day.
