On the other hand, Spain is only the third country that has made the most money through the Champions League, despite having won more titles than any other (five, for the four from Italy, the three from England and the two from Germany).
Distribution
This apparent paradox is explained by the complicated money distribution procedure applied by UEFA.
For this year, the body chaired by Michel Platini plans to enter 1,090 million for the Champions League.
Of this money, UEFA will dedicate 413.1 million for fixed payments: each of the 20 clubs that participated in the previous qualifying round (including Atlético de Madrid) received 2.1 million.
In addition, those who managed to participate received 3.8 million just for being there, in addition to another 550,000 euros for each game they play.
There are also bonuses for winning (800,000 euros) and for drawing (400,000 for each team). The eighth finalists will receive three million each; the eight quarter-finalists, 3.3 million.
The last four will pocket 4 million each.
The champion will win 9 million, compared to 5.2 million for the finalist.
Thus, in terms of fixed payments, a club will enter at least 7.1 million, and a maximum of 31.2 million.
Barça on the other hand, pocketed 2.5 million for winning the European Super Cup in August.
But there are also the variable payments, to which 337.8 million are destined.
This money is distributed according to the proportional value of each television market.
Spanish is one of the main ones, and has four assigned places.
The champion from the previous year keeps 40% of the allocated money, 30% for the second, 20% for the third and 10% for the fourth.
The other part will be paid according to the number of games played in this year&#39;s edition.
